<h3 id="R-squared">R-squared<a class="anchor-link" href="#R-squared"> </a></h3><p>R squared, also known as the <strong>coefficient of determination</strong>, is a measure to indicate how close the data is to the fitted regression line. \
Why I keep getting confused is because there seem to be two similar definitions, one from Statistics and one more used in the ML community. (I'm sure they're derived from the same or similar concept but the way they are presented is confusing.\
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coefficient_of_determination">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coefficient_of_determination</a></p>
<h5 id="Stats">Stats<a class="anchor-link" href="#Stats"> </a></h5><p>Focuses on the definitions that explain $R^2$ as explained variance and as related to the correlation coefficient.</p>
<p>$R^2$: The percentage of variation of the target variable(y) that is explained by the linear model.<br>
like comparing a regression model to a simple model i.e. the <strong>mean of the target data points.</strong><br></p>
<p>These definitions don't talk about how $R^2$ can even be negative if the fit is way worse than the mean of the predictions.</p>
<p>Can be derived easily from variance of two random variables and is related to Pearson's Correlation :</p>
<p>For Random var. x (Actual target) and y (predicted values by model)</p>
<p>The variance of x is the measure of the spread of the probability distribution of the random var.\</p>
<p>$Var(x) = E[(x - E(x))^2]$</p>
<p>which for a population with n data points:</p>
<p>$\sigma^2 = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{(x_i - \bar{x})^2}$</p>
<p>and covariance is the measure of joint variability of two random variables x and y.</p>
<p>$Cov(x, y) = E[(x - E(x))^2(y - E(y))^2]$</p>
<p>Correlation is a measure of interdependence or  relationship b/w two random variables.</p>
<p>Whereas, Pearson's Correlation coefficient or Pearson's r is the most common method of measuring linear correlation in stats.\
Pearson's Correlation is a dimensionless scaled form of covariance:</p>
<p>$\text{Pearson's r} = Cor(x, y) = \frac{Cov(x,y)}{\sqrt{Var(x)Var(y)}}  = \frac{Cov(x,y)}{\sigma_x\sigma_y}$</p>
<p>Which brings us (how ??? ) to $R^2$ or the coefficient of determination as defined in statistics
where  $S_{e}^{2}$ is the sample variance of the residuals and  $S_{y}^{2}$ is the sample variance of the outputs.
:
$R^2 = 1 - \frac{S_{e}^{2}(\text{Uses fitted line})}{S_{y}^{2}(\text{From data points})}$</p>
<h5 id="ML">ML<a class="anchor-link" href="#ML"> </a></h5><p>Focuses on the definition derived from the residual errors, which can be used to derive the MSE. Ultimately gives us the form :</p>
<p>{% raw %}
$$R^2 : 1 -  \frac{MSE_{\text{regression line}}}{MSE_{\bar{y}(\text{average of datapoints})} }$$
{% endraw %}</p>
<p>The score here is the R2 score, or coefficient of determination, which measures how well a model performs relative to a simple mean of the target values.\
R2 = 1 indicates a perfect match,\
R2 = 0 indicates the model does no better than simply taking the mean of the data,\
and negative values mean even worse models.</p>
<h5 id="Limitations-of-R^2">Limitations of R^2<a class="anchor-link" href="#Limitations-of-R^2"> </a></h5><p>R<sup>2</sup> is a proportion but can be misleading, for example just changing the scale of the target to log improved the score, but the model is the same. Another problem is that it is problematic for time-series data etc.</p>
<p>R-squared (From Chirags notebook):</p>
<ul>
<li>A common way to evaluate the overall fit of a linear model</li>
<li>Defined as the proportion of variance explained, meaning the proportion of variance in the observed data that is explained by the model</li>
<li>Also defined as the reduction in error over the null model, which is the model that simply predicts the mean of the observed response</li>
<li>Between 0 and 1, and higher is better</li>
</ul>
<p>The threshold for a "good" R-squared value is highly dependent on the particular domain.</p>
<ul>
<li>R-squared is <strong>more useful as a tool for comparing models.</strong></li>
</ul>
<p>Feature selection
How do I decide which features to include in a linear model?</p>
<ul>
<li>Using R-squared - We could try models with different sets of features, and compare their R-squared values:</li>
<li>R-squared will always increase as you add more features to the model, even if they are unrelated to the response.</li>
<li>As such, using R-squared as a model evaluation metric can lead to overfitting.</li>
<li><strong>Adjusted R-squared</strong> is an alternative that penalizes model complexity (to control for overfitting), but it generally under-penalizes complexity.</li>
<li>As well, R-squared depends on the same assumptions as p-values, and it's less reliable if those assumptions are violated. (Linear models rely upon a lot of assumptions (such as the features being independent), and if those assumptions are violated (which they usually are), p-values are less reliable.)</li>
</ul>

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h4 id="lets-create-a-manual-implementation-of-pearson's-r-and-Coefficient-of-determination-R^2-using-the-statistics-approach">lets create a manual implementation of pearson's r and Coefficient of determination R^2 using the statistics approach<a class="anchor-link" href="#lets-create-a-manual-implementation-of-pearson's-r-and-Coefficient-of-determination-R^2-using-the-statistics-approach"> </a></h4><p>Pearson's Correlation is a dimensionless scaled form of covariance:</p>
<p>$\text{Pearson's r} = Cor(x, y) = \frac{Cov(x,y)}{\sqrt{Var(x)Var(y)}}  = \frac{Cov(x,y)}{\sigma_x\sigma_y}$</p>
<p>$R^2$ or the coefficient of determination as defined in statistics:
where  $S_{e}^{2}$ is the sample variance of the residuals and  $S_{y}^{2}$ is the sample variance of the outputs.
:
$R^2 = 1 - \frac{S_{e}^{2}(\text{Uses fitted line})}{S_{y}^{2}(\text{From data points})}$</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Adjusted-R^2">Adjusted R^2<a class="anchor-link" href="#Adjusted-R^2"> </a></h3><p>is an alternative to R^2 that penalizes model complexity (to control for overfitting), but it generally under-penalizes complexity.\
Defined as : $$ \text{Adj } R^2 = 1-(1-R^2)*\frac{(n-1)}{(n-p-1)} $$</p>
<p>Where  n = number of sample size , p = number of independent variables</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
    {% raw %}
    
<div class="cell border-box-sizing code_cell rendered">
<div class="input">

<div class="inner_cell">
    <div class="input_area">
<div class=" highlight hl-ipython3"><pre><span></span><span class="k">def</span> <span class="nf">adj_r2_score</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">r2</span><span class="p">,</span> <span class="n">x_test</span><span class="p">):</span>
    <span class="sd">&quot;&quot;&quot;Better to extend r2&quot;&quot;&quot;</span>
    <span class="n">adj_r2</span> <span class="o">=</span> <span class="mi">1</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="p">(</span><span class="mi">1</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">r2</span><span class="p">)</span> <span class="o">*</span> <span class="p">((</span><span class="n">x_test</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">)</span><span class="o">/</span><span class="p">(</span><span class="n">x_test</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">0</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="n">x_test</span><span class="o">.</span><span class="n">shape</span><span class="p">[</span><span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">]</span> <span class="o">-</span> <span class="mi">1</span><span class="p">))</span>
    <span class="k">return</span> <span class="n">adj_r2</span>
</pre></div>

    </div>
</div>
</div>

</div>
    {% endraw %}

<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h2 id="More-reliable-Evaluation-metrics-for-regression-problems">More reliable Evaluation metrics for regression problems<a class="anchor-link" href="#More-reliable-Evaluation-metrics-for-regression-problems"> </a></h2><p><strong>MSE</strong> and <strong>MAE</strong> and other error metrics are more suitable error metrics used in ML as the results are more directly comparable given the same scale.</p>
<p>MSE is less robust to ouliers in target compared to MAE.</p>
<ul>
<li>MAE is the easiest to understand, because it's the average error.</li>
<li>MSE is more popular than MAE, because MSE "punishes" larger errors, which tends to be useful in the real world.</li>
<li>RMSE is even more popular than MSE, because RMSE is interpretable in the "y" units.</li>
</ul>

</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="cell border-box-sizing text_cell rendered"><div class="inner_cell">
<div class="text_cell_render border-box-sizing rendered_html">
<h3 id="Time-Series-Metrics">Time-Series Metrics<a class="anchor-link" href="#Time-Series-Metrics"> </a></h3><p>from <a href="https://otexts.com/fpp2/accuracy.html">https://otexts.com/fpp2/accuracy.html</a>: \
A forecast method that minimises the <strong>MAE</strong> will lead to forecasts of the median, while minimising the <strong>RMSE</strong> will lead to forecasts of the mean.</p>
<p>Mean Absolute Percentage Error (<strong>MAPE</strong>): this is the same as MAE but is computed as a percentage, which is very convenient when you want to explain the quality of the model to management,  [0,+)</p>
<p>$MAPE = \frac{100}{n}\sum\limits_{i=1}^{n} \frac{|y_i - \hat{y}_i|}{y_i}$</p>

</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
